00:11:20.450 --> 00:11:21.280
of the shares of the company.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:23.880
These guys get wiped out, even
though the company really was

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:24.810
worth something.

00:11:24.810 --> 00:11:27.030
So let's say the company emerges
from bankruptcy like

00:11:27.030 --> 00:11:30.360
this, but it actually turns out
there were $10 million.

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:31.800
Then let's say a year
later the company

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:33.170
starts doing well again.

00:11:33.170 --> 00:11:35.570
And let's say that someone could
value the company again

00:11:35.570 --> 00:11:36.060
at $10 million.

00:11:36.060 --> 00:11:38.970
Now it only has $2
million of debt.

00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:42.050
And now you have $8 million
worth of equity.

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:45.330
So these guys-- maybe they were
owed $2 or $3 million

00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:48.470
before, and they got $3 million
of the new equity,

00:11:48.470 --> 00:11:49.780
they might have made
out like bandits.

00:11:49.780 --> 00:11:51.790
Because now all of a
sudden, that equity

00:11:51.790 --> 00:11:52.550
could be worth a lot.

00:11:52.550 --> 00:11:53.610
That's not always the case.

00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:56.670
But that's the view from the
debt holders' point of view.

00:11:56.670 --> 00:11:58.510
The equity holders, you can
imagine, they don't want to be

00:11:58.510 --> 00:11:59.980
left with nothing.

00:11:59.980 --> 00:12:01.640
They'll hire their
own bankers.

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:03.315
And their bankers, they'll
probably submit a plan that

00:12:03.315 --> 00:12:03.930
says, no, no, no, no.

00:12:03.930 --> 00:12:06.890
This company is worth
at least $8 million.

00:12:09.680 --> 00:12:11.910
So up here $8 million.

00:12:11.910 --> 00:12:16.470
And we think it can handle
$4 million of debt.

00:12:16.470 --> 00:12:18.550
So they'd want a scenario like
this, where they think the

00:12:18.550 --> 00:12:20.270
company's worth $8 million.

00:12:22.850 --> 00:12:25.060
It can handle $4 million
worth of debt.

00:12:25.060 --> 00:12:28.310
And so it has $4 million
worth of equity.

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:31.520
And of course, the first $6
million of the value-- so the

00:12:31.520 --> 00:12:35.000
$4 million of debt, and then $2
million of the equity will

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:36.940
go to the debt holders, right?

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:40.090
Because they were owed $6
million to begin with.

00:12:40.090 --> 00:12:43.620
And then what's left over, which
is essentially-- so this

00:12:43.620 --> 00:12:45.780
is $2 million of equity, and
then you'd have $2 million of

00:12:45.780 --> 00:12:50.050
equity here-- this $2 million
of new equity, right?

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:52.700
This is the new shares of the
company will be given to the

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:54.470
old shareholders
of the company.

00:12:54.470 --> 00:12:56.320
So that's what the shareholders
want.

00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:59.560
I know this gets a little
confusing, but it all ends up

00:12:59.560 --> 00:13:03.140
being valuing the assets as you
emerge from bankruptcy.

00:13:03.140 --> 00:13:04.020
You say, you know,
it's generating

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:05.500
cash, it's worth something.

00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:08.240
And then you pay people off
according to seniority.

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:09.500
And first you pay them off.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:11.250
You say, OK, I still
owe you some money.

00:13:11.250 --> 00:13:13.960
But this company can't support
$6 million of debt.

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:16.090
It can now support $2 million.

00:13:16.090 --> 00:13:18.680
And whatever's left, people
are paid with actually

00:13:18.680 --> 00:13:21.150
shares-- new shares--
of the company.

00:13:21.150 --> 00:13:22.080
Not the old shares.

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:23.820
So the old shares
will go to 0.

00:13:23.820 --> 00:13:26.560
So you can imagine a world
where GM goes bankrupt.

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:29.520
Right now, the shares
of GM go to 0.

00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:32.330
GM old goes to 0.

00:13:32.330 --> 00:13:34.750
But the assets keep operating,
and that's why some people are

00:13:34.750 --> 00:13:36.970
a little bit misleading in
this whole automotive

00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:37.810
bankruptcy debate.

00:13:37.810 --> 00:13:40.440
They're kind of using scare
tactics to say, oh, if GM goes

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:42.790
bankrupt, then these assets are
just going to disappear.

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:44.070
No, they'll just
keep operating.

00:13:44.070 --> 00:13:46.750
If it makes sense to operate
them, they'll keep operating.

00:13:46.750 --> 00:13:49.170
The only people who
will lose big are

00:13:49.170 --> 00:13:50.620
the old equity holders.

00:13:50.620 --> 00:13:52.900
And then some of the unsecured,
the more junior

00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:55.700
levels of debt, will probably
lose some money.

00:13:55.700 --> 00:13:57.290
But if the assets are
worth operating,

00:13:57.290 --> 00:13:58.175
they'll continue to operate.

00:13:58.175 --> 00:14:00.690
And if the people, if it makes
sense to have them employed,

00:14:00.690 --> 00:14:02.410
they'll keep working.

00:14:02.410 --> 00:14:04.230
See you in the next video.

